The chemosensing of a variety of NACs (1.0 × 10−4 mol L−1) was tested, including p-NP, 2,4,6-trinitrophenol (TNP), m-nitrophenol (m-NP), 2,4-dinitrophenol (DNP), 2,4-dinitrotoluene (DNT), o-nitrophenol (o-NP), p-dinitrobenzene (p-DNB), p-nitrotoluene (p-NT), m-dinitrobenzene (m-DNB), nitrobenzene (NB), and phenol (PhOH), by as-synthesized HBD in DMF, HDASD in DOX, and HDOBD in ACN (Fig. 7
                           ). The reduction of the fluorescence intensity is highly dependent on the NACs nature. Among these NACs, p-NP is the most serious for quenching of fluorescence emission spectra [19]. With an increased concentration of p-NP, the fluorescence intensity decreased continuously (Fig. 7). Noticeably, the fluorescence intensities of the COFs decreased apparently even adding 1.0 × 10−4 mol L−1 p-NP. The quenching constants (Ksv) calculated from the Stern-Volmer plots were 7.91 × 104, 1.16 × 105, and 3.76 × 104, L mol−1, respectively, which are moderate compared to other COF-NAC chemical sensors (Table 1
                           ) [15,17,19]. However, the fluorescence quenching degrees were relatively small for other NACs under the same conditions when the concentration was 1.0 × 10−4 mol L−1, indicating HBD, HDASD, and HDOBD had high sensing selectivity for p-NP to other NACs [19]. Moreover, the limits of detection (LODs) for p-NP were determined as 4.36 × 10−11, 2.59 × 10−10, and 7.98 × 10−11 mol L−1 (Fig. 8
                            and Table 1). These values represent an excellent sensitivity toward p-NP detection, which is superior to many COF chemosensors (Table S3) [21].

To illuminate the fluorescence quenching mechanisms of p-NP and iodine for the COFs, we compared the highest-occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and the lowest-unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) energy levels of the COFs, NACs, iodine, and phenol (Fig. S18 and Table 2
                           ). The energy levels of LUMO of the COFs are higher than that of NACs and iodine, which provide the driving force of electron migration from the COFs to the NACs and iodine, thus causing quenching fluorescence [15,16]. Moreover, the emission spectra of the COFs and UV–Vis spectra of NACs and iodine showed that there were great spectral overlaps of the COFs with iodine, and there was also a spectral overlap of HBD with p-NP. The spectral overlaps implied that energy transfer was occurred, which enhances the fluorescence quenching effects [15]. Therefore, the fluorescence quenching of HBD by o-NP and the three COFs by iodine has both the photo-induced electronic charge transfer and photo-induced energy transfer process [16]. Nevertheless, there were almost no spectral overlaps of HDASD and HDOBD with p-NP, which signified that the fluorescence quenching of p-NP by the HDASD and HDOBD is only the photo-induced electronic charge transfer process (Fig. 9
                           ).
